[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 {Hi, my name is Niclas Huschenbeth and I'm a Grandmaster from Germany. My whole life I've been playing1.e4and enjoying the sharp positions that arise from this first move.In this repertoire, I want to give you aggressive and ambitious lines that players at the beginner level (up to 1600 Elo or 2000 online rating) are not able to cope with. You are going to play lines with which you are often going to end up in clearly better or completely winning positions.Why am I so confident in saying that? Well, I have created this repertoire with a very practical approach in mind. That means I have researched the online Lichess database with over 2 billion (!) games to determine which variations score the best at the beginner level. All the lines you find in this repertoire have been proven statistically to score well, because beginner players usually don't know them and don't have the playing strength to find the correct defensive moves. Plus, all the moves in the repertoire have been checked and approved by Stockfish which has a rating of 3500 Elo.This repertoire works best against players under 1600 Elo or 2000 online rating. With higher ratings, players either know the correct responses or are able to calculate their way out of the complications. Even then, you don't risk anything as with correct play by your opponent, you end up in a position that is equal or in very rare cases, slightly worse for White. At the beginner level, however, you are going to pose unsolvable problems to many of your opponents starting with move 1, and obtain a massive amount of winning positions early on.Have fun with this repertoire!} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Two Knights: 4...d5 5.exd5 Nxd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Nf6 {This opening is called the 'Two Knights Defense'. Black first develops the two knights before bringing the f8-bishop into play.This move is perfectly fine and is also played at the highest level. However, it is quite dangerous for less experienced players, because White can launch a direct attack on the often vulnerable f7-pawn.} 
4. Ng5 {After this maximally aggressive sortie, many of our opponents will start sweating. The f7-pawn is attacked by two minor pieces and is difficult to defend. In this line we have a good chance of getting a winning position directly from the opening.} 
4. d5 {This is already the only move to keep the balance. Of course, we want to put the opponent in a situation where he has to find 'only moves' as often as possible. Because then it's very likely that he will not find it at some point and we are clearly better or even winning.On any other move that we haven't covered yet, our answer is always the same, as shown in this sample line:4...h65.Nxf7+-We win at least a rook thanks to the fork.} 
5. exd5
5. Nxd5 {In about 40% of the games this very natural move is played, although it's a mistake, because it allows a big bang.} 
6. Nxf7 {We sacrifice the knight to drag the king out. The opponent will already have beads of sweat on his forehead here.} 
6. Kxf7
7. Qf3+ {Check and at the same time another attack on the knight on d5.} 
7. Ke8
8. Bxd5 {And another double threat! On the one hand, we threaten mate on f7, on the other hand, we threaten to take twice on c6.} 
8. Qf6
9. Bxc6+
9. Qxc6
10. Qxc6+
10. bxc6
11. d3 {The smoke has cleared. Since we have a healthy extra pawn and Black has a terrible pawn structure, we're already on the winning side.} 
