2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {We are putting our development on hold for the moment as we want to build a strong center first. The push d2-d4 could now follow with gain of tempo, since the bishop on c5 would be attacked. Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. O-O {This line is called the Walbrodt-Baird Gambit, named after Carl Walbrodt and John Baird, two players who used it in the late 19th century. The two most played moves are6...O-Oand6...dxc3.} 
6. dxc3 {This move is played in over 50% of the games. Although objectively this is not yet a mistake, the position is already extremely dangerous for Black.} 
7. e5 {We completely ignore the pawn on c3 and attack the knight on f6 instead. Now Black has only one move that doesn't lose! However, it's only played in about 15% of the games. In other words, we have an almost 85% chance of getting a winning position after just 7 moves.} 
7. Ne4
8. Qd5 {We already know this motif. Due to the double attack on f7 and the knight on e4, Black loses at least a piece.} 
8. O-O {The lesser evil!} 
9. Qxe4
9. cxb2
10. Bxb2 {Now we have a piece for two pawns and also good attacking chances against Black's king.} 
10. d6
11. Bd3 {Threatening mate on h7.} 
11. g6 {This is exactly the weakening we wanted to provoke.} 
12. exd6
12. Bxd6
13. Bc4 {Now all we have to do is bring the queen to c3 and checkmate on the long diagonal. This plan is surprisingly difficult to prevent.} 
