[Black "Moeller Attack: 8...Nxc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with 6.0-0, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with 6. cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as 6.0-0.} 
6. cxd4 {This is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb4+ {This check is necessary, because otherwise we can consolidate and have a clear advantage thanks to our magnificent pawn center.} 
7. Nc3 {We block the check and develop the knight to its natural square. This line is called the Greco Attack or the Moeller Attack, named after the Danish player Jorgen Moeller. I think the latter is more common, so I call it that.} 
7. Nxe4 {Again, this is forced. Black must accept our pawn sacrifice and embark on the dangerous lines that follow. Otherwise we're clearly better.} 
8. O-O {After we get our king to safety, the c3-knight is no longer pinned and the e4-knight is attacked. Black now has an important decision to make about how to take the knight on c3.} 
8. Nxc3 {This is the 'wrong' way of taking on c3. Black is objectively not yet losing, but more than 98% of the players don't find the right continuation after our answer9.bxc3.In other words, you can look forward to getting 8... Nxc3 on the board, because most likely you will now get a winning position.} 
9. bxc3 {We recapture and attack the bishop on b4. Instinctively one wants to take care of the attacked bishop and actually most players either take on c3 (73%) or choose the retreat to e7 (23%). However, these two logical moves are wrong and after both we are clearly winning. The correct and only move is9...d5with a counterattack on our bishop on c4. Not an easy move to find, is it?In this chapter we want to examine the retreat to e7. In the next chapter we look at the alternatives9...Bxc3and the best move9...d5.} 
9. Be7 {That actually looks very solid. As a precaution, the bishop blocks a check on the e-file. If Black could play d7-d5 next, his position would be perfectly fine. But it's our turn and we're really getting started now!} 
10. d5 {We gain space, attack the knight on c6 and prevent Black from making the liberating move d7-d5. The knight only has the two squares available, a5 and b8; our answer is the same after both moves. We play the unbelievably strong second pawn sacrifice d5-d6 and then the black king is soon under attack!} 
10. Na5 {Black puts the knight on the rim, hoping to gain a tempo by attacking the bishop. But we ignore that and play a second powerful pawn sacrifice.} 
11. d6 {We immediately reopen the diagonal of the light-squared bishop and do not allow Black to develop his queenside with d7-d6. Our clear advantage in development is now being transformed into a fearsome attack and there isn't much Black can do about it. The bishop sacrifice on f7 is an important idea in many lines.} 
11. cxd6
12. Bxf7+ {We sacrifice the bishop and develop an irresistible attack on the black king. It works so well because the pieces on the queenside (especially the rook on a8 and the bishop on c8, but also the knight on a5) cannot help with the defense. On the other hand, we can draw on the firepower of our entire army.} 
12. Kxf7
13. Qd5+ {We centralize the queen with check and also keep an eye on the knight on a5, which can be relevant in some lines.} 
13. Kf8
14. Ng5 {Theatening checkmate on f7. I recommend this move because now most players don't find the only chance to stay in the game, which is Qd8-e8. But don't worry, even after this move we keep a winning position. However, it's much more likely that Black will eliminate the knight on g5 and then his position will be absolutely hopeless.14.Bg5is objectively a bit stronger than 14. Ng5, but also a bit more complicated. After14...Nc615.Rfe1+-Black will hardly be able to parry the attack on the open e-file.} 
14. Bxg5 {The dark-squared bishop was an important defender of the king. Its absence will quickly make itself felt.} 
15. Bxg5 {We recapture with the bishop and attack the black queen.} 
15. Qe8
16. Rfe1 {Of course, we can also take the knight on a5 here or in the next moves, but for the moment we are not particularly interested in it. We continue to exert pressure on the black queen and king.} 
16. Qf7
17. Qxd6+
17. Kg8
18. Re7 {Each move comes with tempo, with a check or an attack on a black piece.} 
18. Qg6
19. Qd5+ {We don't exchange queens, but give check and finally relieve the knight on a5 from its suffering.} 
19. Kf8
20. Qxa5 {This is the easiest solution. We have regained the sacrificed material and are threatening mate after Qa5-d8+. If Black plays20...b6, we can reply21.Qd5attacking the a8-rook. Next we bring the second rook to e1 and Black's king will not survive the attack.} 
