5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. cxd4 {This is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb4+ {This check is necessary, because otherwise we can consolidate and have a clear advantage thanks to our magnificent pawn center.} 
7. Nc3 {We block the check and develop the knight to its natural square. This line is called the Greco Attack or the Moeller Attack, named after the Danish player Jorgen Moeller. I think the latter is more common, so I call it that.} 
7. Nxe4 {Again, this is forced. Black must accept our pawn sacrifice and embark on the dangerous lines that follow. Otherwise we're clearly better.} 
8. O-O {After we get our king to safety, the c3-knight is no longer pinned and the e4-knight is attacked. Black now has an important decision to make about how to take the knight on c3. In fact, there is also the rather rare possibility of not taking it at all, but instead castling short.} 
8. Bxc3
9. d5
9. Ne5 {The knight moves to the center, attacks the bishop on c4 and is protected by the hanging bishop on c3. A rather confusing situation, but we can clear things up very soon.} 
10. bxc3 {Now the knight on e5 is threatened by the knight on f3. Logically Black takes our hanging bishop on c4.} 
10. Nxc4 {Did we just lose a piece? Don't worry, that was all part of our plan. We'll get our material back, and often with interest.} 
11. Qd4 {With this powerful move, the queen attacks both (!) knights and the pawn on g7. Black is advised not to cling to the extra piece, but to give up a knight with11...O-O. The only good alternative,11...f5, is very rarely played.} 
11. Ncd6 {Black is clinging to the extra piece, but that's dangerous! However, this move is played in about 54% of the games.} 
12. Qxg7 {This was the third threat Black failed to parry. Now the rook can only be defended in two ways.} 
12. Qf6 {Black protects the rook on h8 and forces the exchange of queens. Are we just a piece down? One might think so, and therein lies the danger for Black, because our attack continues in the endgame. But recognizing this before playing the move 11...Ncd6 is very difficult, and not only for beginners!} 
13. Qxf6
13. Nxf6
14. Re1+ {After this check on the open e-file, Black is faced with an important decision: move the king aside or put a knight in between? The king moves are clearly more popular, but lead to a completely losing position for Black. The problem usually lies in the weakened dark squares, as we shall see.} 
14. Kd8
15. Bg5 {We pin the knight and threaten to take it with a double attack on the king and the h8-rook.} 
15. Nde8 {Black thinks everything is under control after this protective move, but he is way off the mark.} 
16. Rxe8+ {Who says we can't also sacrifice and attack in the endgame? A real bang!} 
16. Kxe8 {This is the usual continuation, but it results in mate in a few moves.} 
17. Re1+
17. Kf8
18. Bh6+ {Off to the corner with the king!} 
18. Kg8
19. Re5 {The threat Re5-g5# can only be parried with a knight move, e.g.19...Ne4. Then, however, mate follows on the back rank with20.Re8#. So we definitely checkmate Black on the next move.} 
