9. d5 {Now Black has two sensible answers, either the counterattack on the c4-bishop with9...Ne5or the retreat9...Bf6.} 
9. Bf6 {This is the most played move and probably also the best. The bishop helps defend Black's position. Now if we take the knight with10.dxc6, Black takes back10...bxc6and is two pawns up. That's why we don't go for the knight on c6, but rather for the one on e4!} 
10. Re1
10. Ne7
11. Rxe4 {We take the knight on e4 and finally got the piece back. We're still a pawn down, but our pieces are active and Black still has problems to solve.} 
11. d6 {This is clearly the most popular move and it makes a lot of sense. Black prevents us from playing d5-d6 and wants to develop the light-squared bishop. We must not release the pressure now!} 
12. Bg5 {We develop the bishop and want to exchange the important defender on f6. Since we threaten to take on f6 and weaken Black's pawn structure, he has to react.} 
12. Bxg5
13. Nxg5
13. h6 {Black drives our knight away from the active position on g5. This is the safest continuation and it's played in about 64% of the games.} 
14. Qa4+ {Even if your opponent know this line up to here, this move will surely surprise him. In the online database it has only been played three times (!) in over 1100 games at beginner level. In the following analysis, I have therefore also included games played at a higher level.14.Qe2is the old main line with the intention of tripling the heavy pieces on the e-file and winning the pinned knight on e7. However, Black has a way of dealing with it well and getting into a clearly better position. Therefore I recommend the rare and objectively stronger14.Qa4+.} 
14. Bd7 {The counterattack on our queen is played almost without exception. After14...Kf8we can withdraw the knight to f3 and Black has lost his castling rights.} 
15. Qb3 {We lured the bishop to d7 so that we can now attack the unprotected pawn on b7. Now you're going to say, 'Wait a minute, what about the knight on g5?' We haven't forgotten it. Yes, Black can take it now, but we will double the rooks on the e-file and recover the knight on e7. Black now either takes on g5 or castles short.} 
15. O-O
16. Rae1 {We bring the rook into play and attack the knight on e7.} 
16. Ng6 {This is the most popular move, and mind you, with an average rating of over 2400 in the online database. However, we now play a nice tactic and have an advantage.16...hxg517.Rxe7transposes to the line 15... hxg5.} 
17. Ne6
17. fxe6
18. dxe6 {Now we are threatening both capturing on d7 and, even stronger, advancing the e-pawn with a fork and a discovered check from the c4-bishop. This means the black king should quickly leave the a2-g8 diagonal.} 
18. Kh8
19. e7 {This is stronger than taking the bishop on d7, because now after the forced19...Nxe7we can place a rook on the seventh rank. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here.} 
