8. O-O
8. b4 {This is the most played move, but now White is already winning!The continuation8...Nc6will be discussed later via the move order 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 e6.} 
9. Nd5 {We move the knight that is being attacked by a pawn to a square where it's also being attacked by a pawn! Such a sharp approach is very typical in the Sicilian. The knight cannot be tolerated on d5, but after taking it, the e-file opens up against the black king and Black's underdevelopment is clearly noticeable.} 
9. exd5
10. Re1 {This is even better than recapturing on d5, because we remain flexible with the e4-pawn. In case of10.exd5Bd611.Re1+Kf8!Black can hope to organize a reasonable defense.The following lines are not about memorization, but rather seeing the general ideas.} 
10. dxe4 {This is the most natural move.} 
11. Ne5 {We bring the knight forward and attack the pawn on f7 a second time.11.Ng5?!is not as strong because after11...d5(which has a big downside after 11. Ne5 instead) there is no convincing follow up for White.} 
11. d5 {The most natural reply; Black blocks the a2-g8 diagonal, but opens up another...} 
12. Ba4+ {This is a very uncomfortable check for Black as he cannot interpose a piece on c6 or d7.} 
12. Ke7 {What else?} 
13. Bg5+ {We come from left and right!} 
13. f6
14. Qb3 {This is very strong. Not only do we threaten to take the pawn on b4 with check and then the bishop on b7, but the threat of taking on e4 with the rook and opening the a2-g8 diagonal for the queen is even stronger. This is illustrated if Black now takes the bishop on g5.} 
14. fxg5
15. Rxe4 {The black king's protection is broken open by force.} 
15. dxe4
16. Qf7+ {That's why we sacrificed the rook: to invade Black's camp with the queen.} 
16. Kd6 {The only move.} 
17. Rd1+ {This is the easiest.} 
17. Kxe5
18. Rxd8 {We have regained the sacrificed material, the black king is on e5 and a few black pieces are still hanging. Black can confidently throw in the towel here.} 
