1. e6 {This is the French Defense. Black plans to occupy the center with d7-d5 and, after a possible exchange on d5, he wants to be able to take back with a pawn. The disadvantage of this opening move is that the light-squared bishop often finds it difficult to get into play, since the development route via e6 is blocked by the pawn. Among beginners, this is the third most popular reply to 1. e4 and it's played in about 10% of the games.} 
2. d4 {If the opponent allows it, we will, of course, occupy the center with both pawns.} 
2. d5 {By also placing a pawn in the center, Black attacks our pawn on e4. We now have many options to respond to this threat; for example, we can advance the pawn (e4-e5), exchange it (e4xd5) or protect it.} 
