1. e4
1. e6 {This is the French Defense. Black plans to occupy the center with d7-d5 and, after a possible exchange on d5, he wants to be able to take back with a pawn. The disadvantage of this opening move is that the light-squared bishop often finds it difficult to get into play, since the development route via e6 is blocked by the pawn. Among beginners, this is the third most popular reply to 1. e4 and it's played in about 10% of the games.} 
2. d4 {If the opponent allows it, we will, of course, occupy the center with both pawns.} 
2. d5 {By also placing a pawn in the center, Black attacks our pawn on e4. We now have many options to respond to this threat; for example, we can advance the pawn (e4-e5), exchange it (e4xd5) or protect it.} 
3. Bd3 {By protecting the pawn on e4 with the bishop, we remain flexible with the development of the king's knight. This move will surprise many opponents and take them straight out of their comfort zone.Now, the standard moves3...c5and above all3...Nf6are already not advisable for Black. The third main move3...dxe4is best.} 
3. dxe4 {The main move is played in 34% of the games. However, it's already new territory for many French players because they don't get the closed structures they would like.} 
4. Bxe4 {We take back with the bishop, which now stays on the h1-a8 diagonal and is a nuisance for Black. For example, it's not so easy for him to bring the light-squared bishop into play due to the attack on the b7-pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {It is very logical to develop the knight and attack the bishop on e4.4...c55.Ne2Nf66.Bf3is analyzed via the move order 4... Nf6 5.Bf3 c5 6. Ne2.} 
5. Bf3 {Usually the f3-square is ideal for the knight. However, here we make an exception and develop the knight to e2 instead. Black now has the choice of either levering the center directly with5...c5or developing his pieces first. Without the c7-c5 lever, however, he will find it difficult to equalize. Otherwise we just control the center and have a little more space for our pieces.} 
5. c5 {Black attacks our central pawn with the typical lever c7-c5.} 
6. Ne2
6. Nc6 {With this move, which is the most frequently played, Black attacks our central pawn a third time, but we can play the same game.} 
7. Be3 {We develop the bishop and defend the pawn on d4 a third time.} 
7. Qb6 {This is the second most popular move. Black attacks the b2-pawn, but as is so often the case, it's dangerous to go pawn-hunting in the opening.} 
8. Nbc3 {We don't waste time on a defensive measure, but instead keep developing!} 
8. cxd4
9. Nxd4 {We threaten a discovered attack on the queen with the e3-bishop by moving the d4-knight. Black now only has one move to avoid being clearly worse!} 
9. Qxb2 {It won't surprise you that this capture doesn't work.} 
10. Ndb5 {We threaten both winning the queen with Ra1-b1 and the fork on c7. Black cannot fend off both threats in the long run.} 
10. Bb4
11. O-O {We have enough time. Both threats still exist and Black cannot take on c3.} 
11. Bxc3
12. Bxc6+ {Other moves win too, but this is the clearest.12...bxc6Now Black is already being mated.13.Nc7+Kf814.Qd8+Ne815.Qxe8} 
