1. e4
1. d5 {The Scandinavian Defense is the fourth most popular opening at beginner level after 1...e5, the Sicilian and the French. Black occupies the center and wants to bring the strongest piece into play early on. However, this approach has the disadvantage that we can gain a tempo by attacking the queen. In addition, we can usually place our other central pawn on d4 and have a long-term space advantage. After studying the presented lines you will be happy if your opponent plays the Scandinavian.} 
2. exd5 {By taking the central pawn, we lure the black queen into the open where we can attack it. However, Black also has other options besides taking the pawn with the queen. Let's look at them first.} 
2. Nf6 {Black would rather recapture on d5 with the knight. Now it's important that we don't cling to the pawn with c2-c4, because then the gambit ...c7-c6 would gain significantly in power if it was accepted. Instead we occupy the center and play natural moves.} 
3. d4
3. Nxd5 {3...Qxd54.Nc3usually leads to a transposition:4...Qa5transposes to the line 3... Qa5, while4...Qd8transposes to the line 3... Qd8.} 
4. c4 {We drive the knight out of the center.} 
4. Nb6 {The knight tends to be a bit worse there than on f6.} 
5. Nf3 {It's important to develop this knight first so that we control the e5-square and prevent a possible counterattack.5.Nc3?!is imprecise because of5...e5!with active counterplay.} 
5. Bg4 {The pin is played most often at the beginner level. However, the bishop is missing on the queenside to defend the light squares.} 
6. c5 {We chase away the knight to then target the pawn on b7 with Qb1-b3.} 
6. Nd5 {That's the natural move, but now we're already winning.After6...N6d7the move7.Qb3would have been less effective. Instead, we should simply continue our development with7.Be2followed by O-O and Be3.} 
7. Qb3 {Black is in trouble because he cannot defend the b-pawn well without severely weakening the light squares.} 
7. Bxf3
8. Qxb7 {An important intermediate move. The rook on a8 is under attack and Bf1-b5+ is also a threat that should not be underestimated. No matter if Black likes it or not, he has to play ...Nd7.} 
8. Nd7
9. gxf3 {And we have an extra pawn and strong control over the light squares.} 
