1. e4
1. c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is a rare guest at beginner level. That's why we don't deal with this opening as intensively as with the other systems. I recommend a rare line, which, however, is quite poisonous, especially at a lower level. As always, we play as aggressively as possible and treat our opponent as unpleasantly as possible!} 
2. Nc3 {2.d4is of course the main line, but I would like to recommend a rare line instead that we can use to surprise the opponent.} 
2. d5
3. Qf3 {This is my recommendation! The move is played in only about 0.1% of games against Caro-Kann, so it will most likely surprise many of your opponents. We put direct pressure on the d5-pawn and have a few tricks up our sleeves in the following lines.Black usually reacts in one of four ways: either he protects the d5-pawn with3...e6or3...Nf6, or he advances it with3...d4or exchanges it with3...dxe4. The latter two moves are the most popular.} 
3. dxe4 {The clear main move is played in about 53% of the games.} 
4. Nxe4 {By recapturing with the knight, we actively place it in the center.} 
4. Nd7 {Black prepares to develop the king's knight to f6.} 
5. Qe3 {I somehow like this tricky move, which, among other things, comes with the threat of the smothered mate Ne4-d6#! Now the best move is5...Ndf6, but almost nobody plays it.5.Bc4?!is not optimal given Black's reply5...Ne5!which not only parries our threat, but can also eliminate our light-squared bishop. However,5.d4is a useful alternative.} 
5. Ngf6
6. Nd6# {Ouch! The queen on e3 pins the pawn on e7 and the black king cannot move at all. A beautiful smothered mate on move 6!} 
