1. e4 {Since this is clearly the most popular first move at amateur level, we're going to examine Black's various options in great detail.} 
1. e5 {Black follows his opponent's example and also puts his e-pawn in the center.} 
2. Nf3 {We develop the knight and attack the central pawn on e5. Now the clear main move is2...Nc6,also developing a piece and protecting the pawn. But first, let's look at all the other continuations.} 
2. f5 {The Latvian Gambit scores surprisingly well at amateur level. However, as with2...f6, moving the f-pawn early is not a good idea.} 
3. Nxe5 {Just like after 2...f6, we take the e5-pawn and directly threaten Qd1-h5+.} 
3. Qf6 {Black defends against the threat of Qd1-h5+ (to which he can now respond with g7-g6) and attacks our knight.} 
4. d4 {Simple and good. We occupy the center and protect the knight.} 
4. d6 {Black drives our knight out of the center.} 
5. Nc4 {This is a better square than f3 or d3, because then we would have to move the knight again after Black takes f5xe4.} 
