[Black "Petrov's Defense: Stafford Gambit 3...Nc6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6 {The Petrov Defense (or Russian Defense) is a rather rare guest at beginner level, and to fight it, many players aim for the   (dubious) Stafford Gambit.} 
3. Nxe5
3. Nc6 {The Stafford Gambit is very popular at beginner level because Black can set a few traps. In fact, this gambit is played more often among beginners than the normal theoretical move3...d6.I'll show you how we avoid any pitfalls and get a winning position straight from the opening. From now on, you'll be happy if your opponents play the Stafford Gambit against you!} 
4. Nxc6 {If you don't feel like getting involved in the Stafford Gambit, you can choose the following simple and good alternative:4.d4±.} 
4. dxc6
5. d3 {We protect the pawn on e4 and prepare the possible development of the queen's bishop. We don't develop the knight b1 to c3 because we often want to build up a strong center with c2-c3 and d3-d4.} 
5. Bc5 {Now Black has the strong threat Nf6-g4 attacking the weakness of f2.} 
6. Be2 {Simple chess. We develop our bishop and protect the square on g4.} 
6. Qd4 {This obvious threat can simply be parried.} 
7. O-O {Now we have the strong threat of expanding the center with c2-c3 and d3-d4.} 
7. h5 {Black dreams of an attack, but our position is rock solid.} 
8. c3 {Now it's the other way round, we're driving back the black pieces!} 
8. Qd6
9. d4 {Black already loses a piece.} 
9. Ng4 {We have to be careful here because of the mating threat on h2.} 
10. e5
10. Qg6
11. dxc5 {We're one piece up and Black's attack is non-existent.} 
