7. c5 {This is the most played move, but it's premature and simply loses the pawn on d6.} 
8. Ndb5 {That's exactly why we developed the bishop to f4.} 
8. a6
9. Nxd6
9. Bxd6 {This is how Black usually plays, but it only makes things worse.} 
10. Bxd6 {10.Qxd6 also leads to a clear winning position.} 
10. Re8
11. O-O-O {Here we can end our analysis. We have the bishop pair, the better development and an extra pawn. Trying to win it back with ...Nxe4 ends in disaster, as shown in the following example line:11...Nxe412.Nxe4Rxe413.Bd3The attacked rook has to move.13...Re814.Bxb8!Rxb8And now a typical tactic that wins an exchange.15.Bxh7+!A classic discovered attack.15...Kxh716.Qxd8Rxd817.Rxd8+-Black can resign.} 
