1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop our next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5. But first, let's look at some rare continuations.} 
3. f5 {Black attacks our center in King's Gambit style, hoping we take the pawn. However, the move has a major disadvantage: the a2-g8 diagonal is weakened and our bishop is already spot on.} 
4. d4 {The strongest continuation!4.d3!?is a simple alternative.4.exf5?is what Black is hoping for. After4...e4Black seizes the initiative.} 
4. exd4
5. e5 {We're down a pawn for the moment, but Black has trouble completing development and, more importantly, getting the king to safety.5.exf5would allow Black to block our bishop with5...d5! =} 
5. d5
6. exd6 {En passant!} 
6. Bxd6
7. O-O {With the push f7-f5, Black has severely weakened his position and he will soon suffer from the consequences.} 
