2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5. But first, let's look at some rare continuations.} 
3. h6 {This is the third most popular move after3...Bc5and3...Nf6.Apparently Black wants to prevent Nf3-g5, but this pawn move doesn't contribute anything to the development and is just too slow. We exploit this downside by immediately becoming active in the center.} 
4. d4
4. exd4
5. Nxd4
5. Nxd4 {Especially among beginners, this exchange is very popular. However, since it leads to an improvement of the position of our queen, we benefit more from it than Black.} 
6. Qxd4
6. Nf6 {The development of the knight runs straight into the following push.} 
7. e5 {Now the knight must either go back to where it came from or move to another unfavorable square.} 
7. Nh7
8. Nc3
8. Be7
9. Qg4 {That's another nasty pinprick. Black has trouble protecting the g7-pawn.} 
9. O-O {This allows the typical motif} 
10. Bxh6 {and we've already won at least one pawn.} 
