1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Nf6 {This opening is called the 'Two Knights Defense'. Black first develops the two knights before bringing the f8-bishop into play.This move is perfectly fine and is also played at the highest level. However, it is quite dangerous for less experienced players, because White can launch a direct attack on the often vulnerable f7-pawn.} 
4. Ng5 {After this maximally aggressive sortie, many of our opponents will start sweating. The f7-pawn is attacked by two minor pieces and is difficult to defend. In this line we have a good chance of getting a winning position directly from the opening.} 
4. Bc5 {The so-called 'Traxler Counterattack' is something we should know because Black has a few tricks up his sleeve.} 
5. Bxf7+ {This is definitely easier than taking with the knight. In case of5.Nxf7Bxf2+!, White's only good reply is6.Kf1. We can save ourselves having to analyze these complications.5.d4!?is a rare alternative which yields great results in practice. Black then needs to play5...d5in order to not be clearly worse.} 
5. Ke7 {Since Black threatens h7-h6 to attack the g5-knight, which protects the f7-bishop, we quickly withdraw the latter.} 
6. Bc4 {This is even better than the retreat to b3, because in some lines we need the bishop as a defender on e2.} 
6. Rf8 {Black now threatens to sacrifice the bishop on f2, which we can easily parry with short castling.} 
7. O-O
7. h6
8. Nf3
8. d6
9. Nc3 {Now we simply complete our development.} 
9. Bg4 {Black pins our knight, but we immediately unpin it.} 
10. Be2 {That's why we put the bishop on c4. Now everything is covered, we have an extra pawn and the safer king.} 
