[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Nf6 {This opening is called the 'Two Knights Defense'. Black first develops the two knights before bringing the f8-bishop into play.This move is perfectly fine and is also played at the highest level. However, it is quite dangerous for less experienced players, because White can launch a direct attack on the often vulnerable f7-pawn.} 
4. Ng5 {After this maximally aggressive sortie, many of our opponents will start sweating. The f7-pawn is attacked by two minor pieces and is difficult to defend. In this line we have a good chance of getting a winning position directly from the opening.} 
4. d5 {This is already the only move to keep the balance. Of course, we want to put the opponent in a situation where he has to find 'only moves' as often as possible. Because then it's very likely that he will not find it at some point and we are clearly better or even winning.On any other move that we haven't covered yet, our answer is always the same, as shown in this sample line:4...h65.Nxf7+-We win at least a rook thanks to the fork.} 
5. exd5
5. b5 {Instead of moving the knight, Black launches a counterattack on our bishop on c4. We should know the right reaction to this ambitious move.} 
6. Bf1 {What a fantastic move! The idea is this: if Black takes with the queen on d5, we want to have the g2-pawn protected.} 
6. Nd4
7. c3 {This transposes to the variation 5...Nd4 which we'll see later.} 
