[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 1.e4 e5 Two Knights: 4.Ng5 Mainline 5...Na5"]
[Black "Two Knights Mainline: 6...c6 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Nf6 {This opening is called the 'Two Knights Defense'. Black first develops the two knights before bringing the f8 bishop into play. The move is perfectly fine and is also played at the highest level. However, it is quite dangerous among beginners, because White can launch a direct attack on the often vulnerable f7-pawn.} 
4. Ng5 {After this maximally aggressive sortie, many of our opponents will start sweating. The f7-pawn is attacked by two minor pieces and is difficult to defend. In this line we have a good chance of getting a winning position directly from the opening.} 
4. d5 {This is already the only move to keep the balance. Of course, we want to put the opponent in a situation where he has to find 'only moves' as often as possible. Because then it's very likely that he will not find it at some point and we are clearly better or even winning.} 
5. exd5
5. Na5 {Someone unfamiliar with this line will most likely not continue in this way. Instead of recapturing the pawn, Black moves the knight to the rim and attacks the bishop on c4. But this is indeed the best line for Black. Depending on your playing strength, you will very rarely get this position on the board.} 
6. Bb5+ {After we move the attacked bishop one square further and give check, Black has two sensible answers.} 
6. c6
7. dxc6
7. bxc6
8. Qf3 {8.Bd3is mainly played at the professional level. For the beginner level, I like the aggressive8.Qf3better, since the two most popular defensive moves8...Bb7and8...Bd7are not really good.} 
8. Be7 {That's a slick move. Black ignores our threat Bb5xc6+ and sacrifices a second pawn. In fact, since taking on c6 is too risky in my opinion, I recommend retreating the bishop.} 
9. Bd3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. h6 {If Black doesn't do anything, we continue our development with Nb1-c3 and Rf1-e1. And Bd3-f5 to swap the light-squared bishops is sometimes an idea too.} 
11. Ne4 {This is our standard reaction after h7-h6. Since we really don't want to put the knight on h3, it's better to exchange it in the center.} 
11. Nd5 {With the strong threat f7-f5.} 
12. Ng3 {We have prevented f7-f5  (we could take the pawn with the knight) and then develop our remaining pieces.} 
