[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.e4 e5 Italian Game: 3.Bc4 Bc5 4.c3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Italian Game Sidelines: 4...Qf6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This is clearly Black's main reply. It develops the knight, protects the pawn on e5 and also fights for the central square on d4.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {We are putting our development on hold for the moment as we want to build a strong center first. The push d2-d4 could now follow with gain of tempo, since the bishop on c5 would be attacked. Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Qf6 {It seems we can't play d2-d4 now, since Black controls the d4-square four times while we only control it three times. But we still make it possible by tactical means.} 
5. d4
5. exd4
6. e5 {This in-between move is the point. Black cannot take the pawn because then he loses a piece. But after he moves the queen away, we can just recapture on d4.} 
6. Nxe5 {This blunder is the most played move in games at the beginner level.} 
7. Qe2 {The knight is pinned and attacked a second time.} 
7. d6
8. cxd4 {Thanks to this fork and the pin on the e-file we will gain a whole piece.} 
