3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {We are putting our development on hold for the moment as we want to build a strong center first. The push d2-d4 could now follow with gain of tempo, since the bishop on c5 would be attacked. Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. d6 {This is how Black plays in about 25% of the games. As we have seen many times, this move is useful, but since it doesn't fight for the center, we are free to occupy it.} 
5. d4 {We occupy the center and directly attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4
6. cxd4 {Now we see the idea behind 4. c2-c3. Since we can take back on d4 with the c-pawn, we have built up a wonderful pawn center.} 
6. Bb6 {The bishop is clearly better on this square than on b4, since it still keeps an eye on the central pawn on d4. Since pinning the knight on f3 with Bc8-g4 would be annoying for us, we continue with the preventive move h2-h3.} 
7. h3 {Now Black cannot develop his bishop onto the active g4-square and put pressure on our center.} 
7. h6 {In many games Black copies our last move. Now we can calmly finish our development.} 
8. Nc3 {We could also start with short castling.} 
8. Nf6
9. O-O
9. O-O
10. Re1 {We support the pawn on e4 one more time.} 
10. Re8
11. Bf4 {What a dream of a position! All our pieces are very active, we have a nice pawn center and more space.} 
