6. O-O {This line is called the Walbrodt-Baird Gambit, named after Carl Walbrodt and John Baird, two players who used it in the late 19th century.Now the two most played moves for Black are6...O-Oand6...dxc3. The best move, on the other hand, is clearly6...Nxe4. But first, let's first look at some rare alternatives.} 
6. d3 {This rare move isn't all that illogical. Black wants to prevent us from building up a strong pawn center.} 
7. e5 {We are in no hurry to win take the pawn on d3. First, let's get the knight in trouble.} 
7. Ng4
8. Bxf7+ {Again the bishop sacrifice on f7! We will come across this motif even more frequently in the Walbrodt-Baird Gambit.} 
8. Kxf7
9. Ng5+ {That is why we lured the king to f7. Black has to react to the check and then we take the knight on g4.} 
9. Ke8
10. Qxg4 {Since Black can no longer castle and will definitely have problems with his king, our advantage is undisputed.} 
