1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
3. Bc4 {We develop the next minor piece. The bishop on c4 controls the central square on d5, but also ogles the weak spot on f7. In many lines this entails tactical motifs.Now the two clear main moves are3...Nf6and3...Bc5.} 
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {We are putting our development on hold for the moment as we want to build a strong center first. The push d2-d4 could now follow with gain of tempo, since the bishop on c5 would be attacked. Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. O-O {This line is called the Walbrodt-Baird Gambit, named after Carl Walbrodt and John Baird, two players who used it in the late 19th century. The two most played moves are6...O-Oand6...dxc3.} 
6. Nxe4 {Many lower ranked players do not dare to take this pawn, probably because they fear the pin on the e-file. Anyway, this move is only played in about 10% of the games.} 
7. cxd4 {The good thing is that Black has to find one more 'only move' to avoid a disadvantage - namely7...d5attacking the bishop on c4. This counterattack is hard to find for many beginners.} 
7. d5 {That's the only way, because after other moves we're at least clearly better. It's precisely this counterattack that is difficult for beginners to find if they don't know the line. Since the first logical reaction is to move away the attacked bishop on c5, it's not surprising that the move is only played in about 9% of the games. And since only 10% of the players find 6...Nxe4 in the first place, you can calculate for yourself how slim the chances are that your opponents will find the best way.} 
8. dxc5
8. dxc4
9. Qe2 {We don't agree to the exchange of queens, but pin the knight instead. Even if Black has made it this far, there are other pitfalls for him to avoid.} 
9. Bf5
10. Nc3 {We attack the pinned knight again.} 
10. Qe7 {This is the most natural move, but it's a mistake.} 
11. Nd5 {This is the disadvantage of Qd8-e7. We bring the knight to the center with tempo and also attack the c7-pawn.} 
11. Qd7
12. Rd1 {All of a sudden Black can't do anything to parry the threatening discovered attack Nd5-f6+.} 
12. O-O-O
13. Nb6+ {Now the discovered attack comes from the other side.} 
13. axb6
14. Rxd7
14. Rxd7
15. cxb6 {We have a queen for a rook and a minor piece, and thus a winning position.} 
