9. d6 {We push the d-pawn forward, attack the knight on e7 and paralyze the further development of Black's queenside, since the d-pawn cannot move for the time being. So the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8 have trouble finding their way into the game.After9.O-Od6!Black can develop the queenside and has survived the worst.} 
9. Nxf2 {This is a very tempting move. Black forks our queen and rook, but we have a strong counter.} 
10. Qb3 {The pawn on f7 is now attacked twice and Black has no time to take the rook on h1.} 
10. Nxh1 {This would lead to disaster.} 
11. Bxf7+
11. Kf8
12. Bg5 {Next we take the knight on e7 and Black has to accept large material losses.} 
