4. c3 {Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. cxd4 {This is the Moeller Attack, which is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb6 {That's too tame. Now, similar to the Walbrodt-Baird Gambit, we can push our central pawns forward and gain more space by attacking the knights.} 
7. d5 {The first knight must move.} 
7. Ne7
8. e5 {And now the second knight must also move.} 
8. Ng4 {Black moves the knight forward and attacks the f2-pawn a second time. However, we can (and should) ignore that and instead push the d-pawn further forward.} 
9. d6 {We push the d-pawn forward, attack the knight on e7 and paralyze the further development of Black's queenside, since the d-pawn cannot move for the time being. So the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8 have trouble finding their way into the game.After9.O-Od6!Black can develop the queenside and has survived the worst.} 
9. Nxf2 {This is a very tempting move. Black forks our queen and rook, but we have a strong counter.} 
10. Qb3 {The pawn on f7 is now attacked twice and Black has no time to take the rook on h1.} 
10. O-O
11. Bg5 {Taking directly on e7 would also be good, but the annoying pin is even stronger. We now threaten to take on e7 with a pawn fork and collect more material. We can always move the attacked rook on h1 later  (or even castle short!). Black loses material and we're winning. Incidentally, in all of these lines it makes little or no difference whether Black exchanges pawns on d6.} 
