[Black "Moeller Attack: 7...Bxc3+ #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. cxd4 {This is the Moeller Attack, which is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb4+ {This check is necessary, because otherwise we can consolidate and have a clear advantage thanks to our magnificent pawn center.} 
7. Nc3 {We block the check and develop the knight to its natural square. This line is called the Greco Attack or the Möller Attack, named after the Danish player Jorgen Möller. I think the latter is more common, so I call it that.} 
7. Bxc3+ {This exchange is premature.} 
8. bxc3
8. Nxe4 {Otherwise we move our pawns forward in the center or alternatively protect them and have fantastic central control. Black now wants to occupy the center himself with d7-d5, attack the bishop on c4 and support the knight on e4. But it's our turn and we prevent it by playing d4-d5 ourselves!} 
9. d5 {The knight on c6 is attacked and must move.} 
9. Ne7
10. Qd4 {By placing the queen in the center, we attack both the knight on e4 and the pawn on g7. That doesn't leave Black with many options.} 
10. Nf6
11. Bg5 {We delay castling for the moment and increase the pressure on Black's position. Now taking twice on f6 threatens to gain a pawn.} 
11. Nf5 {Black attacks our queen, but on f5 the knight tends to be vulnerable.} 
12. Qf4
12. d6
13. g4 {The knight has to retreat. If it moves back to e7, we can take on f6 and then castle long. The king's rook moves to the open e-file and the black king feels pretty uncomfortable. And after Nf5-h6 we can take the knight on h6 and then play Ke1-d2 or O-O-O to clear the way for our rooks to get onto the e-file. In both cases we put the white king on the queenside, since we have already weakened the kingside with g2-g4.} 
