2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. cxd4 {This is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb4+ {This check is necessary, because otherwise we can consolidate and have a clear advantage thanks to our magnificent pawn center.} 
7. Nc3 {We block the check and develop the knight to its natural square. This line is called the Greco Attack or the Moeller Attack, named after the Danish player Jorgen Moeller. I think the latter is more common, so I call it that.} 
7. Nxe4 {Again, this is forced. Black must accept our pawn sacrifice and embark on the dangerous lines that follow. Otherwise we're clearly better.} 
8. O-O {After we get our king to safety, the c3-knight is no longer pinned and the e4-knight is attacked. Black now has an important decision to make about how to take the knight on c3.} 
8. Nxc3 {This is the 'wrong' way of taking on c3 Black is objectively not yet losing, but more than 98% of the players don't find the right continuation after our answer9.bxc3.In other words, after 8... Nxc3 you can already look forward to it, because most likely you will now get a winning position.} 
9. bxc3 {We recapture and attack the bishop on b4. Instinctively one wants to take care of the attacked bishop and actually most players either take on c3 (73%) or choose the retreat to e7 (23%) . However, these two logical moves are wrong and after both we are clearly winning. The correct and only move is 9... d5 with a counterattack on our bishop on c4. Not an easy move, is it?} 
9. Bxc3 {This is the move which Black chooses in over 70% of the games, but it's a serious mistake. The bishop will be missed on the diagonal a3-f8 and we can keep Black's king in the middle by occupying the mentioned diagonal with Bc1-a3.The nice thing is that the refutation of9...Bxc3is much easier and we have to remember fewer lines than after the second most popular move9...Be7.} 
10. Ba3 {We ignore the attack on the a1-rook and put our bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. This prevents Black from castling short since the bishop controls the f8-square. Thus, the king is stuck in the middle and a check on the open e-file would have fatal consequences. Because of this, Black cannot take the a1-rook. But either way, good advice is expensive.} 
10. d6
11. Rc1 {We move the attacked rook to c1 and in turn attack the bishop on c3.} 
11. Ba5
12. Qa4 {This is an important move. We pin the c6-knight and threaten to win it with d4-d5. At the same time we also keep an eye on the bishop on a5. This means that even if the knight can move away from c6 after the attack, the bishop on a5 is lost. Black is simply losing.} 
12. a6 {This is Black's best try. Now Black could react to d4-d5 by playing b7-b5. This is why we attack the knight c6 in a different way.} 
13. Bd5 {We threaten to trade the knight on c6 and win the bishop on a5 subsequently.} 
13. Bb6
14. Rxc6
14. Bd7 {Black tries to save himself with this pin.} 
15. Re1+
15. Kf8
16. Rxd6 {What a move! We unpin and sacrifice the rook in order to continue our attack against the black king.} 
16. cxd6
17. Bxd6+
17. Kg8 {There are many ways to victory for White as our pieces are simply too effective for Black to organize a sufficient defense.} 
18. Ng5 {We offer our queen on a4 once more. The threat is checkmate in one move with Bd5xf7++.} 
18. Qxg5
19. Qxd7 {Black will not be able to defend against the various mating threats.} 
