10. bxc3 {Now the knight on e5 is threatened by the knight on f3. Logically Black takes our hanging bishop on c4.} 
10. Nxc4 {Did we just lose a piece? Don't worry, that was all part of our plan. We'll get our material back, and often with interest.} 
11. Qd4 {With this powerful move, the queen attacks both (!) knights and the pawn on g7. Black is advised not to cling to the extra piece, but to give up a knight with11...O-O. The only good alternative,11...f5, is very rarely played.} 
11. Ncd6 {Black is clinging to the extra piece, but that's dangerous! However, this move is played in about 54% of the games.} 
12. Qxg7 {This was the third threat Black failed to parry. Now the rook can only be defended in two ways.} 
12. Qf6 {Black protects the rook on h8 and forces the exchange of queens. Are we just a piece down? One might think so, and therein lies the danger for Black, because our attack continues in the endgame. But recognizing this before playing the move 11...Ncd6 is very difficult, and not only for beginners!} 
13. Qxf6
13. Nxf6
14. Re1+ {After this check on the open e-file, Black is faced with an important decision: move the king aside or put a knight in between? The king moves are clearly more popular, but lead to a completely losing position for Black. The problem usually lies in the weakened dark squares, as we shall see.} 
14. Nfe4 {This is the only move to avoid being clearly worse or even losing. Only about 9% of players find it.} 
15. Nd2 {We attack the pinned knight again and also clear the way for the f-pawn.} 
15. f5
16. f3 {After finally getting back the piece that was sacrificed a long time ago, we are a little more comfortable thanks to our active pieces.} 
