4. c3 {Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. cxd4 {This is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb4+ {This check is necessary, because otherwise we can consolidate and have a clear advantage thanks to our magnificent pawn center.} 
7. Nc3 {We block the check and develop the knight to its natural square. This line is called the Greco Attack or the Moeller Attack, named after the Danish player Jorgen Moeller. I think the latter is more common, so I call it that.} 
7. Nxe4 {Again, this is forced. Black must accept our pawn sacrifice and embark on the dangerous lines that follow. Otherwise we're clearly better.} 
8. O-O {After we get our king to safety, the c3-knight is no longer pinned and the e4-knight is attacked. Black now has an important decision to make about how to take the knight on c3. In fact, there is also the rather rare possibility of not taking it at all, but instead castling short.} 
8. Bxc3
9. d5 {Now Black has two sensible answers, either the counterattack on the c4-bishop with9...Ne5or the retreat9...Bf6.} 
9. Bf6 {This is the most played move and probably also the best. The bishop helps defend Black's position. Now if we take the knight on c6, Black takes back and is two pawns up. That's why we don't go for the knight on c6, but rather for the one on e4!} 
