[White "26) 1.e4 e5 Moeller Attack: 8...Bxc3 9.d5 Bf6 Mainline"]
[Black "Moeller Attack: 8...Bxc3 9.d5 Bf6 with 13...h6 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Bc5 {Black also develops his bishop and increases his control of the d4-square. That's why we can't play the direct central push d2-d4, but have to prepare it first. By the way, we can't play Nf3-g5 either, since this square is protected by the black queen.} 
4. c3 {Next we answer almost every black move with d2-d4.} 
4. Nf6 {This is clearly the best move. Black develops another piece and attacks the e4-pawn.} 
5. d4 {Instead of protecting the pawn, we play our usual central push and attack the bishop on c5.} 
5. exd4 {This is forced. In this position I would like to make two recommendations. On the one hand, the simple Walbrodt-Baird Gambit with6.O-O, which scores particularly well at lower levels. On the other hand, the Moeller Attack with6.cxd4, which is a bit more complicated but at least as dangerous as6.O-O.} 
6. cxd4 {This is my second recommendation in the Italian Game. We recapture on d4 and build up a strong center. Black now has to react vigorously to avoid a clear disadvantage.} 
6. Bb4+ {This check is necessary, because otherwise we can consolidate and have a clear advantage thanks to our magnificent pawn center.} 
7. Nc3 {We block the check and develop the knight to its natural square. This line is called the Greco Attack or the Moeller Attack, named after the Danish player Jorgen Moeller. I think the latter is more common, so I call it that.} 
7. Nxe4 {Again, this is forced. Black must accept our pawn sacrifice and embark on the dangerous lines that follow. Otherwise we're clearly better.} 
8. O-O {After we get our king to safety, the c3-knight is no longer pinned and the e4-knight is attacked. Black now has an important decision to make about how to take the knight on c3. In fact, there is also the rather rare possibility of not taking it at all, but instead castling short.} 
8. Bxc3
9. d5 {Now Black has two sensible answers, either the counterattack on the c4-bishop with9...Ne5or the retreat9...Bf6.} 
9. Bf6 {This is the most played move and probably also the best. The bishop helps defend Black's position. Now if we take the knight with10.dxc6, Black takes back10...bxc6and is two pawns up. That's why we don't go for the knight on c6, but rather for the one on e4!} 
10. Re1
10. Ne7
11. Rxe4 {We take the knight on e4 and finally got the piece back. We're still a pawn down, but our pieces are active and Black still has problems to solve.} 
11. d6 {This is clearly the most popular move and it makes a lot of sense. Black prevents us from playing d5-d6 and wants to develop the light-squared bishop. We must not release the pressure now!} 
12. Bg5 {We develop the bishop and want to exchange the important defender on f6. Since we threaten to take on f6 and weaken Black's pawn structure, he has to react.} 
12. Bxg5
13. Nxg5
13. h6 {Black drives our knight away from the active position on g5. This is the safest continuation and it's played in about 64% of the games.} 
14. Qa4+ {Even if your opponent know this line up to here, this move will surely surprise him. In the online database it has only been played three times (!) in over 1100 games at beginner level. In the following analysis, I have therefore also included games played at a higher level.14.Qe2is the old main line with the intention of tripling the heavy pieces on the e-file and winning the pinned knight on e7. However, Black has a way of dealing with it well and getting into a clearly better position. Therefore I recommend the rare and objectively stronger14.Qa4+.} 
14. Bd7 {The counterattack on our queen is played almost without exception. After14...Kf8we can withdraw the knight to f3 and Black has lost his castling rights.} 
15. Qb3 {We lured the bishop to d7 so that we can now attack the unprotected pawn on b7. Now you're going to say, 'Wait a minute, what about the knight on g5?' We haven't forgotten it. Yes, Black can take it now, but we will double the rooks on the e-file and recover the knight on e7. Black now either takes on g5 or castles short.} 
15. hxg5
16. Rae1
16. Be6 {This is a typical defensive idea in the mainline with 14. Qe2, but it doesn't work so well here.} 
17. R4e3 {Very precise. The rook prophylactically avoids a later attack with d6-d5. Also, after taking on e6, it's a typical idea to invade Black's position with Re3-h3. Black cannot yet take the defensive position with f7-f6, because then we would take on e6 with the rook.} 
17. c6
18. dxe6 {Only now!} 
18. f6
19. Qxb7 {We have won back the pawn and are clearly better. The pawn on e6 is a thorn in Black's side, the light squares are weakened and the black king cannot find a safe haven.Incidentally, instead of19.Qxb7,19.Rh3is also a strong move.} 
