[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. d4 {The Morra Gambit! We sacrifice a pawn early in the game to get open files and be able to quickly develop our troops. At a lower level, this opening is very dangerous for Black.} 
2. cxd4 {Black should take the pawn on d4. After other moves, our bold push would not be 'punished' and we would be clearly better straight away, since we have more space for our pieces.} 
3. c3 {We don't recapture the pawn with the queen, but attack it with the c-pawn. Now we threaten to take c3xd4 and build up a strong center, similar to the openings we play after 1. e4 e5. In over 70% of the games the Morra Gambit is accepted, which means that Black takes the pawn on c3. In this chapter, let's look at what happens if the gambit is declined.} 
3. Nf6 {This is my own recommendation (on Modern Chess) for Black's Sicilian repertoire. However, among beginners this move is only played in 4% of the games.} 
4. e5 {We move the attacked pawn and, in turn, attack the knight on f6.} 
4. Nd5
5. Nf3 {In the spirit of the Morra Gambit, we continue to offer the pawn on c3 in the next few moves. At the moment Black can't take it anyway. For instance,5...dxc3??drops the knight to6.Qxd5+-.} 
5. e6
6. cxd4 {Now is a good time to recapture the pawn, as Black could now take on c3 without having to worry about losing the d5-knight.} 
6. Nc6
7. Bc4 {We usually move this bishop to d3 or c4.} 
7. Nb6
8. Bb3
8. d6
9. Qe2 {In this way we avoid exchanging queens if the d-file opens after a pawn exchange on e5. Next we castle and bring our pieces from the queenside into play. Thanks to the space advantage, we're in a better position.} 
