[White "28) 1.e4 c5: Morra Gambit 4th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Morra Gambit: 4...e6 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. d4 {The Morra Gambit! We sacrifice a pawn early in the game to get open files and be able to quickly develop our troops. At a lower level, this opening is very dangerous for Black.} 
2. cxd4 {Black should take the pawn on d4. After other moves, our bold push would not be 'punished' and we would be clearly better straight away, since we have more space for our pieces.} 
3. c3 {We don't recapture the pawn with the queen, because then Black could develop the knight with tempo (attacking the queen). Instead, we offer a pawn  (that's why it's called 'Gambit') to speed up our development and open lines for our pieces.} 
3. dxc3 {In over 70% of the games, Black accepts the sacrifice. This is good news for us because we have the easier play and can set up many pitfalls for our opponent to trip over.} 
4. Nxc3 {We recapture the pawn and develop our knight to c3.} 
4. e6 {4...e55.Nf3Nc6transposes to the line 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 e5.} 
5. Nf3
5. a6 {A sensible move. Black controls the b5-square and can play b7-b5 himself to develop his light-squared bishop to b7. On the other hand, he neglects the development of the kingside, which we can exploit powerfully in certain lines.5...Nc6is analyzed via the move order 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 e6.} 
6. Bc4 {We develop our bishop to c4 as usual. The knight move to c6 at this moment and in the next few moves leads to a line that will be discussed under 4... Nc6.} 
6. b5
7. Bb3
7. Bb7
8. O-O
8. b4 {This is the most played move, but now White is already winning!The continuation8...Nc6will be discussed later via the move order 4...Nc6 5. Nf3 e6.} 
9. Nd5 {We move the knight that is being attacked by a pawn to a square where it's also being attacked by a pawn! Such a sharp approach is very typical in the Sicilian. The knight cannot be tolerated on d5, but after taking it, the e-file opens up against the black king and Black's underdevelopment is clearly noticeable.} 
9. exd5
10. Re1 {This is even better than recapturing on d5, because we remain flexible with the e4-pawn. In case of10.exd5Bd611.Re1+Kf8!Black can hope to organize a reasonable defense.The following lines are not about memorization, but rather seeing the general ideas.} 
10. Be7 {Black tries to block the e-file as a precaution.} 
11. exd5 {Now we take on d5 and directly threaten to win the pinned bishop on e7 with d5-d6. Black's answer is therefore as logical as it is forced.} 
11. d6
12. Bf4 {We bring the last minor piece into play and keep an eye on the d6-pawn. For example, Black cannot develop the knight to d7, since we can then take on d6 with the bishop.If we'd start with12.Ba4+?!instead, then12...Nd7!13.Bf4Kf8!is much less clear. Black would be able to put his d7-knight on c5 or e5 on the next move.} 
12. Nf6 {Watch out, because Black threatens to slip away with short castling!} 
13. Ba4+ {After this very precise check, Black has no good response and must, willy-nilly, give up the dream of castling.} 
13. Nbd7
14. Bxd6 {That's why we developed our bishop to f4. The pinned bishop on e7 is lost and we get the material back with interest.} 
