12. Bf4 {We bring the last minor piece into play and keep an eye on the d6-pawn. For example, Black cannot develop the knight to d7, since we can then take on d6 with the bishop.If we'd start with12.Ba4+?!instead, then12...Nd7!13.Bf4Kf8!is much less clear. Black would be able to put his d7-knight on c5 or e5 on the next move.} 
12. Nf6 {Watch out, because Black threatens to slip away with short castling!} 
13. Ba4+ {After this very precise check, Black has no good response and must, willy-nilly, give up the dream of castling.} 
13. Kf8
14. Nd4 {14.Ng5?h6∓doesn't do anything for White. Instead, the knight strives for f5, from where it attacks the bishop on e7 again. Our attack is very strong.} 
14. Kg8 {This sidestep cleares the f8-square for the bishop.} 
15. Bg5 {Above all, the threat Nd4-f5 causes Black big problems. Here the move order is important, since the immediate15.Nf5?allows Black to consolidate with15...Bf8and now16.Bg5can just be answered by16...h617.Bxf6Qxf6∓.15.Bg5!introduces a pin on the f6-knight. This is important after the continuation15...Bf8when16.Re8!wins the queen (16...Nxe817.Bxd8). The immediate15...h616.Bxf6Bxf617.Re8+is similar.} 
