10. e5 {That's why we placed the rook on d1, opposite of Black's queen. Our plan is now working perfectly.} 
10. Ne8 {At least Black can protect the pawn on d6 one more time.} 
11. exd6 {The immediate11.Bf4allows11...d5!} 
11. Nxd6
12. Bf4 {We increase the pressure on the pinned knight and threaten to attack it again with Nc3-e4.This is stronger than first12.Ne4, as then Black can step out of the pin with12...Qc7!with a tempo on the bishop on c4, and can exchange on e4 on the next move. Meanwhile, after12.Bf4Qc7White can just move the b3-bishop back with13.Bb3when the d6-knight is still pinned.} 
12. Qb6 {Black has unpinned the knight and parried our threat. In addition, he threatens to eliminate our beautiful bishop on c4, so it simply retreats to a safe square.} 
13. Bb3 {Black has avoided direct loss of material but definitely remains under pressure. You just have to compare the activity of the pieces!} 
