[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) 1.e4 c5: Morra Gambit 4...d6"]
[Black "Morra Gambit: 4...d6 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. d4 {The Morra Gambit! We sacrifice a pawn early in the game to get open files and be able to quickly develop our troops. At a lower level, this opening is very dangerous for Black.} 
2. cxd4 {Black should take the pawn on d4. After other moves, our bold push would not be 'punished' and we would be clearly better straight away, since we have more space for our pieces.} 
3. c3 {We don't recapture the pawn with the queen, because then Black could develop the knight with tempo (attacking the queen). Instead, we offer a pawn  (that's why it's called 'Gambit') to speed up our development and open lines for our pieces.} 
3. dxc3 {In over 70% of the games, Black accepts the sacrifice. This is good news for us because we have the easier play and can set up many pitfalls for our opponent to trip over.} 
4. Nxc3 {We recapture the pawn and develop our knight to c3.} 
4. d6
5. Bc4 {This is a clever move order. Normally we develop the king's knight first, but here we set a trap.} 
5. Nf6 {This is the most played move, although it's very dangerous for Black!5...Nc66.Nf3is analyzed via the move order 4... Nc6 and 5... d6.} 
6. e5 {It's because of this trick that we first developed the bishop.} 
6. Ng4
7. e6 {We cut off the cover of the g4-knight from the c8-bishop. Since we also threaten to take the pawn on f7 with check, the answer is forced.} 
7. Ne5 {Black managed to parry both threats and even set up one himself: the bishop on c4 is attacked.} 
8. Bb5+ {8.exf7+Nxf79.Nf3followed by castling short is also good for White.} 
8. Nbc6
9. f4 {Thanks to powerful play, we don't give Black a breather.} 
9. Ng6
10. h4 {We won't leave the knight alone! Now h4-h5 threatens to win it since it has run out of squares.} 
10. h5 {This is the only way Black can keep the knight, although it weakens the squares on g5 and g6.} 
11. exf7+
11. Kxf7
12. Nf3 {With the insertion of h4 and h5, Black's position has been considerably weakened and White has great play against the king.} 
