[Black "Morra Gambit: 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 e6 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. d4 {The Morra Gambit! We sacrifice a pawn early in the game to get open files and be able to quickly develop our troops. At a lower level, this opening is very dangerous for Black.} 
2. cxd4 {Black should take the pawn on d4. After other moves, our bold push would not be 'punished' and we would be clearly better straight away, since we have more space for our pieces.} 
3. c3 {We don't recapture the pawn with the queen, because then Black could develop the knight with tempo (attacking the queen). Instead, we offer a pawn (that's why it's called 'Gambit') to speed up our development and open lines for our pieces.} 
3. dxc3 {In over 70% of the games, Black accepts the sacrifice. This is good news for us because we have the easier play and can set up many pitfalls for our opponent to trip over.} 
4. Nxc3 {We recapture the pawn and develop our knight to c3.} 
4. Nc6
5. Nf3 {The next moves are usually identical for us. The knight is well-placed on f3, the bishop belongs to c4 and afterwards we play short castle. Only in a few exceptions we deviate from this setup.} 
5. e6
6. Bc4
6. Nf6
7. O-O {Since after any bishop move White has the unpleasant threat e4-e5, Black should now play7...d6which transposes to the mainline 5... d6.} 
7. Qc7 {With this move Black not only prevents e4-e5, but also has a diabolical trap in mind. Since I once painfully fell into it as a kid, I definitely want to mention it here.7...Bb4transposes to the line 6... Bb4.} 
8. Re1 {We renew the threat e4-e5, but don't allow tricks with Nf6-g4. Incidentally, Nc3-d5 is also an idea, for example after now ...Ng4.Our thematic move8.Qe2is not the best choice here. Black sets a trap with8...Ng4, when after9.h3??it snaps shut:9...Nd4!-+ and White has to give up the queen to avoid mate with10.Nxd4Qh2#.} 
8. d6 {Black prevents e4-e5, but his queen is wrongly placed on c7. We can punish him with powerful play.} 
9. Nb5 {This is a typical motif if the queen is on c7 and Black hasn't controlled the b5-square with a7-a6.} 
9. Qb8
10. Bf4 {Yet another attack on the weakling on d6!} 
10. e5
11. Qb3 {We come from the right and from the left! Now Black can't protect the f7-pawn, but he shouldn't take the bishop on f4 either.} 
11. exf4
12. e5 {We open the position against the king left in the middle.} 
12. dxe5
13. Bxf7+ {This will not end well for Black.} 
13. Ke7
14. Rad1 {The poor black king is attacked by all our pieces and won't survive.} 
