[White "31) 1.e4 c5: Morra Gambit 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 e6"]
[Black "Morra Gambit: 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 e6 #14"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. d4 {The Morra Gambit! We sacrifice a pawn early in the game to get open files and be able to quickly develop our troops. At a lower level, this opening is very dangerous for Black.} 
2. cxd4 {Black should take the pawn on d4. After other moves, our bold push would not be 'punished' and we would be clearly better straight away, since we have more space for our pieces.} 
3. c3 {We don't recapture the pawn with the queen, because then Black could develop the knight with tempo (attacking the queen). Instead, we offer a pawn (that's why it's called 'Gambit') to speed up our development and open lines for our pieces.} 
3. dxc3 {In over 70% of the games, Black accepts the sacrifice. This is good news for us because we have the easier play and can set up many pitfalls for our opponent to trip over.} 
4. Nxc3 {We recapture the pawn and develop our knight to c3.} 
4. Nc6
5. Nf3 {The next moves are usually identical for us. The knight is well-placed on f3, the bishop belongs to c4 and afterwards we play short castle. Only in a few exceptions we deviate from this setup.} 
5. e6
6. Bc4
6. Bb4 {The setup ...Bb4 followed by ...Nge7 is very reasonable, because it avoids the often annoying push e4-e5.6...d6is analyzed via the move order 5... d6 6. Bc4 e6.} 
7. O-O
7. Nge7
8. Qe2 {Once again we strive for our typical setup. The queen clears the way for the rook, which can move to d1 next.} 
8. O-O
9. Rd1
9. Bxc3
10. bxc3
10. d5
11. Bd3 {It's important not to reflexively take on d5, because that would only help Black to develop (the bishop on c8 can start breathing).} 
11. Qa5
12. e5 {Now the bishop sacrifice on h7 is always in the air.} 
12. Ng6
13. Rb1 {We have wonderful compensation for the sacrificed pawn. If Black takes on c3, the rook can be activated with Rb1-b3 etc. via the third rank. h2-h4-h5 is also an idea to keep the attack going.} 
