2. d4 {The Morra Gambit! We sacrifice a pawn early in the game to get open files and be able to quickly develop our troops. At a lower level, this opening is very dangerous for Black.} 
2. cxd4 {Black should take the pawn on d4. After other moves, our bold push would not be 'punished' and we would be clearly better straight away, since we have more space for our pieces.} 
3. c3 {We don't recapture the pawn with the queen, because then Black could develop the knight with tempo (attacking the queen). Instead, we offer a pawn (that's why it's called 'Gambit') to speed up our development and open lines for our pieces.} 
3. dxc3 {In over 70% of the games, Black accepts the sacrifice. This is good news for us because we have the easier play and can set up many pitfalls for our opponent to trip over.} 
4. Nxc3 {We recapture the pawn and develop our knight to c3.} 
4. Nc6
5. Nf3 {The next moves are usually identical for us. The knight is well-placed on f3, the bishop belongs to c4 and afterwards we play short castle. Only in a few exceptions we deviate from this setup.} 
5. d6
6. Bc4 {The two clear main moves are now6...Nf6and6...e6.} 
6. e6 {This is the precise move order for Black. Next, the minor pieces on the kingside can be developed.} 
7. O-O
7. Nf6
8. Qe2
8. Be7
9. Rd1 {It's quite likely that you will get this position in one of your games via one or the other move order. Black has only made natural moves, but is already in great danger. The two best moves9...e5and9...Bd7are only played in a total of 25% of the games. Meanwhile, the two most popular moves,9...O-Oand9...Qc7, lead to a clearly better or even winning position for us.} 
9. e5 {Black prevents all e4-e5 ideas, and this is certainly his best move from a practical perspective.} 
10. Bb5 {A cunning move. Suddenly the pawn e5 is hanging due to various pins.} 
10. O-O
11. Bxc6 {Since the knight is currently protecting the pawn on e5, we need to eliminate it first before taking the pawn.} 
11. bxc6
12. Nxe5 {This is possible because the d6-pawn is pinned. We now threaten to win another pawn on c6.} 
12. Qc7 {Black protects the pawn and removes the queen from the d-file. Our knight is now attacked by the d6-pawn.} 
13. Nf3 {We have won back the sacrificed pawn and can now bring the remaining pieces on the queenside into play. The position is a bit easier to play for White.} 
