1. e4
1. e6 {This is the French Defense. Black plans to occupy the center with d7-d5 and, after a possible exchange on d5, he wants to be able to take back with a pawn. The disadvantage of this opening move is that the light-squared bishop often finds it difficult to get into play, since the development route via e6 is blocked by the pawn.Among beginners, this is the third most popular reply to 1. e4 and it's played in about 10% of the games.} 
2. d4 {If the opponent allows it, we will, of course, occupy the center with both pawns.} 
2. d5 {By also placing a pawn in the center, Black attacks our pawn on e4. We now have many options to respond to this threat; for example, we can advance the pawn (e4-e5), exchange it  (e4xd5) or protect it.} 
3. Bd3 {By protecting the pawn on e4 with the bishop, we remain flexible with the development of the king's knight. This move will surprise many opponents and take them straight out of their comfort zone.Now, the standard French moves3...c5and above all3...Nf6are already not advisable for Black. The third main move3...dxe4is best. In addition, we will briefly take a look at3...Nc6.} 
3. Nf6 {Black attacks the e4-pawn once more, but this is exactly the move we were waiting for!} 
4. e5 {We gain space and attack the knight, which has to move again.} 
4. Nfd7 {The knight is worse on d7 than on g8. It targets e5, but we can simply support the pawn with f2-f4. On the other hand, the knight on d7 hampers many other black pieces.} 
5. f4 {Here we see one of the ideas of the 3. Bd3 system. Since our two knights are still on b1 and g1, we can support the center with the pawn moves f2-f4 and c2-c3. Against this massive pawn chain Black cannot do anything effective in the near future.} 
5. c5 {This is Black's typical pawn lever in the French Defense.} 
6. c3 {By protecting the pawn on d4, we keep our pawn chain intact.} 
6. Nc6 {Black develops the knight and attacks the d4-pawn again.} 
7. Nf3 {And we also develop our knight and protect the pawn. So far everything is clear.} 
7. Qb6 {Black persists and attacks the d4-pawn a third time. Of course, we cannot put the dark-squared bishop on e3, because then the b2-pawn would be unprotected.} 
8. Bc2 {In this way we support the protection of the d4-pawn with the queen and Black cannot increase the pressure on the center any further.} 
8. cxd4 {Black exchanges pawns to gain access to the b4-square.} 
9. cxd4
9. Nb4 {Black wants to eliminate our strong light-squared bishop, but loses valuable time.} 
10. O-O {We just continue our development. If we move our bishop10.Bb3or10.Ba4, Black has the strong reply10...Qa6!} 
10. Nxc2 {Otherwise we could avoid the exchange on the next move by putting the bishop on a4 or b3.} 
11. Qxc2
11. Be7
12. Nc3
12. O-O
13. Be3 {We finished our development with natural moves and are a bit better thanks to the clear space advantage. The knight on d7 seems especially out of place. Depending on Black's continuation, f4-f5 with a possible attack against Black's king can be an interesting idea.} 
