[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e6 {This is the French Defense. Black plans to occupy the center with d7-d5 and, after a possible exchange on d5, he wants to be able to take back with a pawn. The disadvantage of this opening move is that the light-squared bishop often finds it difficult to get into play, since the development route via e6 is blocked by the pawn. Among beginners, this is the third most popular reply to 1. e4 and it's played in about 10% of the games.} 
2. d4 {If the opponent allows it, we will, of course, occupy the center with both pawns.} 
2. d5 {By also placing a pawn in the center, Black attacks our pawn on e4. We now have many options to respond to this threat; for example, we can advance the pawn (e4-e5), exchange it (e4xd5) or protect it.} 
3. Bd3 {By protecting the pawn one4with the bishop, we remain flexible with the development of the king's knight. This move will surprise many opponents and take them straight out of their comfort zone. Now, the standard moves3...c5and above all3...Nf6are already not advisable for Black. The third main move3...dxe4is best.} 
3. c5 {Black attacks our pawn center with a lever.} 
4. exd5 {We take the pawn in the center. Black is faced with the decision to recapture with the queen or the pawn.} 
4. Qxd5 {A tempting move, because Black is now attacking two pawns. But we can actually parry both threats skillfully!} 
5. Nc3 {We simply develop the knight and attack the queen on d5. As is so often the case, we prefer to focus on development rather than the number of pawns. In fact, it's best for Black not to take either pawn and play5...Qd8. In practice, however, this move is only played in 12% of the games.} 
5. Qxg2 {Now the trap will snap shut! Black is greedy and grabs the pawn, simultaneously attacking the h1-rook. However, that will cost him dearly.} 
6. Be4 {We attack the queen and at the same time protect the rook on h1. And a closer look reveals that the queen has no escape squares and is therefore lost.} 
