3. Bd3 {By protecting the pawn on e4 with the bishop, we remain flexible with the development of the king's knight. This move will surprise many opponents and take them straight out of their comfort zone.Now, the standard moves3...c5and above all3...Nf6are already not advisable for Black. The third main move3...dxe4is best.} 
3. dxe4 {The main move is played in 34% of the games. However, it's already new territory for many French players because they don't get the closed structures they would like.} 
4. Bxe4 {We take back with the bishop, which now stays on the h1-a8 diagonal and is a nuisance for Black. For example, it's not so easy for him to bring the light-squared bishop into play due to the attack on the b7-pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {It is very logical to develop the knight and attack the bishop on e4.4...c55.Ne2Nf66.Bf3is analyzed via the move order 4... Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2.} 
5. Bf3 {Usually the f3-square is ideal for the knight. However, here we make an exception and develop the knight to e2 instead. Black now has the choice of either levering the center directly with5...c5or developing his pieces first. Without the c7-c5 lever, however, he will find it difficult to equalize. Otherwise we just control the center and have a little more space for our pieces.} 
5. c5 {Black attacks our central pawn with the typical lever c7-c5.} 
6. Ne2
6. Nc6 {With this move, which is the most frequently played, Black attacks our central pawn a third time, but we can play the same game.} 
7. Be3 {We develop the bishop and defend the pawn on d4 a third time.} 
7. cxd4
8. Nxd4 {We recapture with the knight and bring it into the center. Now the knight on c6 is threatened twice and Black has to react.} 
8. Ne5 {This is the only move to avoid a disadvantage.} 
9. Nc3 {We develop the last minor piece and let Black take on f3 if he wants to.} 
9. Bb4 {Black puts the bishop on an active square and pins our knight.} 
10. Ndb5 {Now we could recapture on c3 with the knight. We also have offensive ideas such as the fork on c7. Black still has problems to solve.} 
10. O-O {This looks logical, but loses an exchange:} 
11. Qxd8
11. Rxd8
12. Nc7 {Once again, the a8 rook is our prey.} 
12. Rb8
13. Bxa7 {Now Black loses the exchange on b8. However, there is one more important detail to ensure that our knight on c7 cannot get caught afterwards.} 
13. Nxf3+
14. gxf3
14. Bd7
15. Bxb8
15. Rxb8 {Now Black threatens to win our knight with Rb8-c8. That's why our answer is forced.} 
16. a4 {Now we can bring the knight back to b5 and are clearly better.} 
