[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5 {The Scandinavian Defense is the fourth most popular opening at beginner level after 1...e5, Sicilian and French. Black occupies the center and wants to bring the strongest piece into play early on. However, this approach has the disadvantage that we can gain a tempo by attacking the queen. In addition, we can usually place our other central pawn on d4 and have a long-term space advantage. After studying the presented lines you will be happy if your opponent plays the Scandinavian.} 
2. exd5 {By taking the central pawn, we lure the black queen into the open where we can attack it.} 
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3 {We develop the knight, attack the black queen and force it to move again.} 
3. Qe5+ {Black gives check, but the queen will definitely not be able to stay on e5 and Black loses more time.} 
4. Be2
4. Bg4 {This is Black's main idea in this line. After other moves, we just continue our development.} 
5. d4 {We put the d-pawn in the center and attack the black queen.} 
5. Bxe2 {Black takes our bishop and attacks our queen. We don't let that confuse us and just recapture.} 
6. Ngxe2 {We have developed another piece and Black still has to react to the attack on his queen.} 
6. Qh5
7. d5 {We gain more space and prevent Black from developing naturally. Next we play the bishop to f4 and place the queen nicely in the center on d4. If Black plays e7-e5, we take en passant and weaken the opponent's structure.} 
