[Black "Scandinavian: 3...Qd8 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5 {The Scandinavian Defense is the fourth most popular opening at beginner level after 1...e5, Sicilian and French. Black occupies the center and wants to bring the strongest piece into play early on. However, this approach has the disadvantage that we can gain a tempo by attacking the queen. In addition, we can usually place our other central pawn on d4 and have a long-term space advantage. After studying the presented lines you will be happy if your opponent plays the Scandinavian.} 
2. exd5 {By taking the central pawn, we lure the black queen into the open where we can attack it.} 
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3 {We develop the knight, attack the black queen and force it to move again.} 
3. Qd8
4. d4 {We occupy the center and clear the way for our dark-squared bishop.} 
4. Nf6
5. Nf3
5. Bg4
6. h3 {This is basically our standard reaction to the pin with Bc8-g4 in the Scandinavian Defense. Black is now faced with the uncomfortable choice of either giving up the bishop pair or withdrawing the bishop and allowing us to expand on the kingside. A clear win-win situation for us!} 
6. Bh5
7. g4 {Many beginners who are learning the principles of opening play are careful with such moves, as White's kingside is permanently weakened. However, we can certainly accept the weakening here, because the advantages clearly outweigh the disadvantages. We gain space on the kingside, push back the bishop and can fianchetto our bishop on g2. We're not obliged to castle short, but even if we do, the bishop protects our king and the push of the g-pawn doesn't matter that much.} 
7. Bg6
8. Ne5 {This is our typical follow-up move. It's best to memorize this sequence of h2-h3, g2-g4 and Nf3-e5 in response to the pin Bc8-g4. By the way, the position is already objectively won for White.} 
8. Nbd7 {Now Black threatens to take on e5 and then exchange queens, but we can prevent that in a clever way.} 
9. Qe2 {The knight on e5 remains a thorn in Black's side. If he exchanges it, we capture with the d-pawn and directly attack the f6 knight. Otherwise, h3-h4-h5 is the typical plan to catch the bishop on g6.} 
