[Black "Caro-Kann: 3...e6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6 {The Caro-Kann Defense is a rare guest at beginner level. That's why we don't deal with this opening as intensively as with the other systems. I recommend a rare line which is quite poisonous, especially at a lower level. As always, we play as aggressively as possible and treat our opponent as unpleasantly as possible!} 
2. Nc3 {2.d4is of course the main line, but I would like to recommend a rare line instead that we can use to surprise the opponent.} 
2. d5
3. Qf3 {This is my recommendation! The move is played in only about 0.1% of games against Caro-Kann, so it will most likely surprise many of your opponents. We put direct pressure on the d5-pawn and have a few tricks up our sleeves in the following lines.Black usually reacts in one of four ways: either he protects the d5-pawn with3...e6or3...Nf6, or he advances it with3...d4or exchanges it with3...dxe4. The latter two moves are the most popular.} 
3. e6 {Black supports the pawn, but leaves the center to us and closes the diagonal of the light-squared bishop so that it can't get in front of the pawn chain. We're already better.} 
4. d4 {We occupy the center.} 
4. Nf6
5. e5 {As in the French Defense, we like to push the pawn and attack the knight with tempo.} 
5. Nfd7
6. Qg3 {This transposes to a line we'll see after 3... Nf6.} 
