1. e4 {Finally, let's look at two knight moves on move 1 that very few of your opponents will play.} 
1. Nc6 {The' Nimzowitsch Defense' is named after a famous master of the past - Aron Nimzowitsch. Now it's easiest to reply2.Nf3,since in most cases this leads to a transposition to openings with 1. e4 e5. After the most played move2...e5we are in familiar territory; for3.Bc4see the 1. e4 e5 chapters.} 
2. Nf3 {2.d4d5!is surprisingly well playable for Black.} 
2. d6
3. d4 {Now nothing speaks against occupying the center with a second pawn.} 
3. Bg4 {To this pin, which is usually played, we have a powerful answer.} 
4. d5 {We attack the knight on c6 and provoke Black to attack our pinned knight again.} 
4. Ne5 {That's exactly what we wanted!} 
5. Nxe5 {After this brilliant queen sacrifice, we will soon get back the sacrificed material with interest.} 
5. Bxd1 {In case of5...dxe56.Qxg4+-Black is simply a piece down.} 
6. Bb5+ {That's our point: Black cannot handle this check in a reasonable way.} 
6. c6 {This solution to the problem is only temporary.} 
7. dxc6 {Now we threaten either c6-c7+ with check and winning the queen, or taking on b7 (again with check) and an attack on the rook. Since Black cannot take well on c6, he has to come up with something else.} 
7. Qa5+ {Black brings the queen out of danger with check and attacks our bishop. However, this defensive measure still doesn't solve the problems.} 
8. Nc3 {We parried both threats and still have strong threats of our own.} 
8. bxc6 {Now we're going to collect loads of material.} 
9. Bxc6+
9. Kd8
10. Nxf7+
10. Kc8
11. Bxa8 {We already have rook, knight and two pawns for the sacrificed queen. And since Black will definitely lose more material, we have a winning position.} 
