[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "48) Rare openings: 1...Nf6 & 1...Nc6"]
[Black "Alekhine Defense: 1...Nf6 #9"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 {Finally, let's look at two knight moves on move 1 that very few of your opponents will play.} 
1. Nf6 {The 'Alekhine Defense' is named after the fourth world champion Alexander Alekhine. Black attacks our central pawn and we accept the invitation to gain a tempo by pushing it forward.} 
2. e5 {The black knight must move again.} 
2. Nd5
3. d4 {We occupy the center and gain space.} 
3. d6 {This is the typical move to leverage our advanced pawns and bring the black pieces into play. I now recommend a rare move from my youth that has earned me a point or two.} 
4. Bc4 {The bishop comes into play and attacks the knight on d5. Objectively this move gives White no advantage, but in practice your opponents will be surprised and most players will not find the right way.} 
4. Nb6 {Black continues in this way in over 70% of the games. Black parries the attack and in turn attacks the bishop on c4.} 
5. Bb3
5. dxe5 {Black wants to open the d-file and swap queens. That would actually be disadvantageous for us, but we have a strong intermediate move.} 
6. Qh5 {We remove the queen from the d-file and attack the pawn on f7 a second time. To parry this threat, Black now plays either6...e6or6...g6.} 
6. e6
7. dxe5 {The e5-pawn controls important squares and Black will subsequently have difficulties finding good squares for his pieces. In particular, the bishop on c8 does not come into play easily.} 
7. Nc6 {This is by far the most popular move, but not the best. In fact Black has only one move to keep the balance and that is7...a5.This opening and especially this move (4% of the games) is so rare that we won't bother with it any further.} 
8. Nf3
8. g6 {Black chases away our queen from its active post, but weakens the dark squares in the long term.} 
9. Qg4
9. Bg7
10. Bg5 {We develop the bishop with tempo and aim straight for the weakened f6-square.} 
10. Qd7
11. Nc3 {Development comes first! Given the strong threat Ra1-d1, we sacrifice the pawn on e5.} 
11. Nxe5
12. Nxe5
12. Bxe5
13. Rd1 {We attack the queen which cannot leave the d-file due to the mate on d8! So Black is in a precarious position.} 
13. Bd6
14. Bf6 {Here we can end our analysis. We have total control over the dark squares and Black's pieces are oddly placed. The king feels unsafe in the middle, but castling short is also not attractive because of the bishop on f6. We would only need to bring the queen to h6 and mate on g7 would no longer be avoidable. We're definitely winning here.} 
