8. Bxf7+ {Again, the typical bishop sacrifice on f7 works perfectly!8.Qd5?This is not good this time given Black's reply.8...Qe7∓Black can protect everything and is even better.} 
8. Kxf7 {Now we're even spoiled for choice on how to get the piece back. Both moves, 9.Qd5+ and 9.Ng5+, lead to a winning position. I will discuss both and you can then decide which one you like better.8...Kf8Now we simply won the pawn on f7.9.Nxc3We're in no rush to withdraw the bishop because if Black takes it, the same motif (Qd1-d5+) would still work.9...Ngxe5Black grabs the pawn on e5, but this opens more lines.10.Nxe5Nxe511.Bb3Now we bring the bishop to safety and the poor king on f8 has almost no protection.11...d612.Bf4We want to eliminate the knight because it covers important squares.12...Qf6Black parries the threat Bf4xe5 and attacks the bishop on f4.13.Nd5We protect the bishop and attack both the queen and the pawn on c7.13...Qf514.Bxe5Before we take on c7, we first exchange the bishop so that it cannot be taken by the queen.14...Qxe514...dxe515.Nxc7+-We attack the rook on a8 and threaten mate on d8 - not a good situation for Black.15.Nxc7It's going to be pitch black for Black.15...Rb816.Re1+-And Black has to give up the queen, because if it leaves the e-file, mate on e8 follows.16...Qf6??17.Re8} 
9. Ng5+ {This move is tempting because most players (about 45%) now choose Kf7-g8, resulting in a mate in 2 moves. However, the positions after 9...Ke8 are a bit more difficult to play and you have to find precise moves to get a winning position.9.Qd5+This is a simple alternative. With the double attack on the king and the bishop we win back the piece.9...Ke89...Kf810.Qxc5+10...d610...Qe711.Qxe7+Surprisingly, in this position we swap queens. This is because the material is already equal and Black still has major coordination problems in the endgame.11.Qxc3Ngxe5This is not as clear as we would like it to be.11...Nxe711...Kxe712.Nxc312...Ngxe5This doesn't end well.13.Nxe5Nxe514.Re1The pin on the e-file puts Black in trouble.14...Kf614...d615.f4+-Now the knight is lost.15.Nd5++-The c7-pawn falls and the black king is roaming around.12.Nxc3Simple chess!12...d613.exd6cxd614.Rd1+-We'll win the pawn on d6, while Black is still having trouble getting his remaining pieces into play.11.exd6Qxd612.Qxc3+-The material is balanced, but the weak king on f8 worries Black a lot.10.Qxc5Qe7For10...cxb211.Bxb2see 7...cxb2.10...d611.exd6Qxd612.Re1+Kf813.Qxc3+-Compared to the line after 9...Kf8, we even got the rook move to e1 for free. We don't complain about that.11.Qxc3This time we keep the queens on the board since Black cannot take on e5.11.Qxe7+This alternative would also lead to a winning position.11...Rf811...Ngxe5With this greedy move, Black conjures up problems on the now open e-file.12.Nxe5Nxe512...Qxe513.Re1+-Thanks to the pin we win the queen. This is the difference between the black king on e8 or f8.13.Re1Since the knight is attacked twice but protected only once, Black doesn't have much choice.13...d614.f4+-The pinned knight is lost and we can even continue our attack.12.Re1+-With everything covered we simply develop our remaining pieces. The black king remains a problem. And the best thing is, we didn't even sacrifice any material for this dream position!} 
9. Ke8 {This is clearly the best move and now we need to continue precisely in order not to spoil our winning position.9...Kg8??Now we don't conquer the knight, but the black king!10.Qd5+10...Kf811.Qf79...Kf810.Qxg4With the strong threat Dg4-f4+ followed by Df7 mate.10...Nxe511.Qf5+!This is important because three threats are being set up at the same time.11...Qf6Black parries the check and protects the knight. But we had attacked a third point...12.Nxh7+!The fork against the king and queen means that Black has to give up the rook for the knight.12...Rxh713.Qxh7Ng4This looks aggressive, but actually doesn't threaten that much.13...d614.Nxc3+-We are a whole exchange up, while Black has a vulnerable king.14.Qh8+First, we force the black king into a worse position.14...Ke714...Kf715.Qh5++-With this triple attack we gain more material.15.Nxc3By developing the knight, we directly threaten a powerful fork on d5.15...Bxf2+This is only one harmless check.16.Kh1+-Black's position is hopeless.} 
10. Qxg4
10. d6 {Black attacks our queen and the pawn on e5.10...Nxe511.Qg3!This is clearly stronger than pinning the knight with Rf1-e1. Because after d7-d6 the queen has to move anyway due to the attack by the bishop on c8.11...d612.Nxc3+-Next we play Bc1-f4 to exchange the knight on e5, which is still blocking the e-file. A very important point here is that the black king has already moved and castling is no longer possible. So the king stays in the middle for a long time and is chronically weak.} 
11. e6 {After parrying both threats, we now threaten something ourselves: the fork Ng5-f7!} 
11. Ne5 {Black protects the f7-square and attacks our queen.} 
12. Qg3 {This is a difficult move. Our queen takes a step back, but keeps an eye on the opposing knight.} 
12. Qe7 {Black wants to get rid of the annoying pawn on e6.} 
13. Nxc3
13. Bxe6
14. Re1 {Sooner or later the defenders have to move away from the e-file and clear the way to the black king, which has already moved and therefore lost the castling rights.} 
